</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Behçet disease is a chronic, relapsing, systemic disorder of unknown etiology, characterized by recurrent oral and genital ulcers, uveitis, and other clinical manifestations in multiple organ systems. Although the diagnosis is made on the basis of the combination of typical clinical symptoms, radiologic findings of Behçet disease show characteristic features of its involvement in the gastrointestinal, neurologic, cardiovascular, and thoracic organ systems. In the gastrointestinal tract, Behçet disease may produce various types of ulcers in the esophagus, stomach, and small and large intestines, as well as deeply penetrating ulcerations in the ileocecal region, with frequently accompanying enteric fistulas. Neurologic involvement includes typical and atypical parenchymal neurobehcet disease, dural sinus thrombosis, cerebral arterial aneurysm, occlusion, dissection, and meningitis. Vascular involvement is divided into three subsets including venous occlusion, arterial occlusion, and arterial aneurysm. Cardiac manifestations include intracardiac thrombus, endomyocardial fibrosis, periaortic pseudoaneurysm, and rupture of the sinus of Valsalva. Manifestations of Behçet disease in the thorax include pulmonary arterial aneurysm, pulmonary arterial thromboembolism, thrombosis in the superior vena cava, pulmonary infarction, hemorrhage, and vasculitis of the pleura and pericardium. These various manifestations of Behçet disease respond to steroid treatment; however, one of the characteristics of Behçet disease is the high rate of complications and recurrence after surgery. Familiarity with its various radiologic and clinical characteristics is essential in making an accurate early diagnosis and for prompt treatment of patients with Behçet disease.</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.e31">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.e31">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f1a.jpeg" height="986" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F1A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1a.</b>  Esophageal ulcer in a 51-year-old man with dysphagia. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows concentric wall thickening (*) in the distal esophagus. <b>(b)</b> Esophagography reveals that the wall thickening is caused by focal ulceration. <b>(c)</b> Endoscopy shows a conglomerated longitudinal ulceration with a sharp margin.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F1A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f1b.jpeg" height="1280" width="481" aria-labelledby="F1B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1b.</b>  Esophageal ulcer in a 51-year-old man with dysphagia. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows concentric wall thickening (*) in the distal esophagus. <b>(b)</b> Esophagography reveals that the wall thickening is caused by focal ulceration. <b>(c)</b> Endoscopy shows a conglomerated longitudinal ulceration with a sharp margin.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F1B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f1c.jpeg" height="1280" width="1190" aria-labelledby="F1C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1c.</b>  Esophageal ulcer in a 51-year-old man with dysphagia. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows concentric wall thickening (*) in the distal esophagus. <b>(b)</b> Esophagography reveals that the wall thickening is caused by focal ulceration. <b>(c)</b> Endoscopy shows a conglomerated longitudinal ulceration with a sharp margin.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F1C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f2a.jpeg" height="1280" width="933" aria-labelledby="F2A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2a.</b>  Esophagobronchial fistula in a 37-year-old man with dysphagia. <b>(a)</b> Esophagography shows contrast medium leaking (arrowhead) to an adjacent bronchus in the left lower lobe. <b>(b)</b> A chest radiograph shows an area of multiple, high-density nodules with consolidation in the left lower lobe, indicating aspiration pneumonia and the presence of barium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F2A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f2b.jpeg" height="1280" width="1102" aria-labelledby="F2B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2b.</b>  Esophagobronchial fistula in a 37-year-old man with dysphagia. <b>(a)</b> Esophagography shows contrast medium leaking (arrowhead) to an adjacent bronchus in the left lower lobe. <b>(b)</b> A chest radiograph shows an area of multiple, high-density nodules with consolidation in the left lower lobe, indicating aspiration pneumonia and the presence of barium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F2B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f3a.jpeg" height="976" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F3A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3a.</b>  Downhill varix of the esophagus in a 64-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows that the caliber of the SVC is decreased and filling defects (arrows) are noted in the SVC and in the left brachicephalic vein. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial CT images at different levels show multiple collateral vessels bilaterally in the mediastinum and paravertebral areas, around the esophagus, in anterior chest wall and diaphragm, and in the intrahepatic area. <b>(d)</b> Coronal CT image shows strong enhancement (arrowheads) along the internal wall of the esophagus, indicating a downhill varix. These findings are compatible with the presence of an esophageal downhill varix caused by SVC obstruction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F3A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f3b.jpeg" height="992" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F3B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3b.</b>  Downhill varix of the esophagus in a 64-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows that the caliber of the SVC is decreased and filling defects (arrows) are noted in the SVC and in the left brachicephalic vein. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial CT images at different levels show multiple collateral vessels bilaterally in the mediastinum and paravertebral areas, around the esophagus, in anterior chest wall and diaphragm, and in the intrahepatic area. <b>(d)</b> Coronal CT image shows strong enhancement (arrowheads) along the internal wall of the esophagus, indicating a downhill varix. These findings are compatible with the presence of an esophageal downhill varix caused by SVC obstruction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F3B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f3c.jpeg" height="1090" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F3C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3c.</b>  Downhill varix of the esophagus in a 64-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows that the caliber of the SVC is decreased and filling defects (arrows) are noted in the SVC and in the left brachicephalic vein. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial CT images at different levels show multiple collateral vessels bilaterally in the mediastinum and paravertebral areas, around the esophagus, in anterior chest wall and diaphragm, and in the intrahepatic area. <b>(d)</b> Coronal CT image shows strong enhancement (arrowheads) along the internal wall of the esophagus, indicating a downhill varix. These findings are compatible with the presence of an esophageal downhill varix caused by SVC obstruction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F3C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f3d.jpeg" height="1280" width="940" aria-labelledby="F3D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3d.</b>  Downhill varix of the esophagus in a 64-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows that the caliber of the SVC is decreased and filling defects (arrows) are noted in the SVC and in the left brachicephalic vein. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial CT images at different levels show multiple collateral vessels bilaterally in the mediastinum and paravertebral areas, around the esophagus, in anterior chest wall and diaphragm, and in the intrahepatic area. <b>(d)</b> Coronal CT image shows strong enhancement (arrowheads) along the internal wall of the esophagus, indicating a downhill varix. These findings are compatible with the presence of an esophageal downhill varix caused by SVC obstruction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F3D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f4a.jpeg" height="1280" width="1040" aria-labelledby="F4A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4a.</b>  Ulceration in the ileocecal region in a 68-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Barium study shows a large discrete ulceration (arrow) at the terminal ileum. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows focal wall thickening (arrowhead) of the terminal ileum, with mesenteric fat infiltration around the ileocecal area. <b>(c)</b> Colonoscopy shows a deep ulceration with a sharp margin at the terminal ileum. <b>(d)</b> Gross specimen demonstrates the focal ulceration with mucosal convergence and hemorrhage (dotted circle).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F4A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f4b.jpeg" height="1082" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F4B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4b.</b>  Ulceration in the ileocecal region in a 68-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Barium study shows a large discrete ulceration (arrow) at the terminal ileum. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows focal wall thickening (arrowhead) of the terminal ileum, with mesenteric fat infiltration around the ileocecal area. <b>(c)</b> Colonoscopy shows a deep ulceration with a sharp margin at the terminal ileum. <b>(d)</b> Gross specimen demonstrates the focal ulceration with mucosal convergence and hemorrhage (dotted circle).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F4B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f4c.jpeg" height="1276" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F4C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4c.</b>  Ulceration in the ileocecal region in a 68-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Barium study shows a large discrete ulceration (arrow) at the terminal ileum. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows focal wall thickening (arrowhead) of the terminal ileum, with mesenteric fat infiltration around the ileocecal area. <b>(c)</b> Colonoscopy shows a deep ulceration with a sharp margin at the terminal ileum. <b>(d)</b> Gross specimen demonstrates the focal ulceration with mucosal convergence and hemorrhage (dotted circle).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F4C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f4d.jpeg" height="767" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F4D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4d.</b>  Ulceration in the ileocecal region in a 68-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Barium study shows a large discrete ulceration (arrow) at the terminal ileum. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows focal wall thickening (arrowhead) of the terminal ileum, with mesenteric fat infiltration around the ileocecal area. <b>(c)</b> Colonoscopy shows a deep ulceration with a sharp margin at the terminal ileum. <b>(d)</b> Gross specimen demonstrates the focal ulceration with mucosal convergence and hemorrhage (dotted circle).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F4D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f5a.jpeg" height="1103" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F5A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5a.</b>  Aneurysmal dilatation of the distal ileum in a 28-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows a long segmental bowel wall thickening with aneurysmal dilatation (*) in the distal ileum. <b>(b)</b> Barium study reveals that this wall thickening is caused by a large area of ulceration (arrow) with converging mucosal folds.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F5A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f5b.jpeg" height="1098" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F5B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5b.</b>  Aneurysmal dilatation of the distal ileum in a 28-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows a long segmental bowel wall thickening with aneurysmal dilatation (*) in the distal ileum. <b>(b)</b> Barium study reveals that this wall thickening is caused by a large area of ulceration (arrow) with converging mucosal folds.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F5B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f6a.jpeg" height="731" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F6A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6a.</b>  Postoperative recurrence of small bowel involvement of Behçet disease in a 35-year-old man who underwent enterostomy. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows multifocal areas of bowel wall thickening (arrowheads) involving the distal ileum and ascending colon, suggestive of postoperative recurrence of Behçet disease. <b>(b)</b> Small-bowel series shows multifocal deep ulcerations (arrowheads) along the distal ileum near the anastomotic site. <b>(c)</b> Gross specimen shows recurrent discrete ulcers in the ileum, matching the radiologic findings.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F6A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f6b.jpeg" height="1089" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F6B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6b.</b>  Postoperative recurrence of small bowel involvement of Behçet disease in a 35-year-old man who underwent enterostomy. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows multifocal areas of bowel wall thickening (arrowheads) involving the distal ileum and ascending colon, suggestive of postoperative recurrence of Behçet disease. <b>(b)</b> Small-bowel series shows multifocal deep ulcerations (arrowheads) along the distal ileum near the anastomotic site. <b>(c)</b> Gross specimen shows recurrent discrete ulcers in the ileum, matching the radiologic findings.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F6B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f6c.jpeg" height="594" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F6C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6c.</b>  Postoperative recurrence of small bowel involvement of Behçet disease in a 35-year-old man who underwent enterostomy. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows multifocal areas of bowel wall thickening (arrowheads) involving the distal ileum and ascending colon, suggestive of postoperative recurrence of Behçet disease. <b>(b)</b> Small-bowel series shows multifocal deep ulcerations (arrowheads) along the distal ileum near the anastomotic site. <b>(c)</b> Gross specimen shows recurrent discrete ulcers in the ileum, matching the radiologic findings.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F6C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f7a.gif" height="440" width="384" aria-labelledby="F7A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7a.</b>  Typical neurobehcet lesions in a 52-year-old man. <b>(a–c)</b> Serial T2-weighted MR images (repetition time msec/echo time msec = 4000/95) show ill-defined high-signal-intensity areas (arrowhead) involving the right thalamus, crus cerebri, cerebral peduncle, and midbrain.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F7A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f7b.gif" height="440" width="422" aria-labelledby="F7B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7b.</b>  Typical neurobehcet lesions in a 52-year-old man. <b>(a–c)</b> Serial T2-weighted MR images (repetition time msec/echo time msec = 4000/95) show ill-defined high-signal-intensity areas (arrowhead) involving the right thalamus, crus cerebri, cerebral peduncle, and midbrain.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F7B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f7c.gif" height="440" width="414" aria-labelledby="F7C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7c.</b>  Typical neurobehcet lesions in a 52-year-old man. <b>(a–c)</b> Serial T2-weighted MR images (repetition time msec/echo time msec = 4000/95) show ill-defined high-signal-intensity areas (arrowhead) involving the right thalamus, crus cerebri, cerebral peduncle, and midbrain.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F7C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f8a.jpeg" height="1280" width="1109" aria-labelledby="F8A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8a.</b>  Atypical neurobehcet lesion in a 30-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> T1-weighted MR image (500/10) shows a large area of low signal intensity (arrow) in the left parietotemporal lobe. <b>(b)</b> Gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (500/10) shows strong enhancement of the masslike lesion, mimicking an abscess. <b>(c)</b> Follow-up MR image obtained after steroid treatment shows a marked decrease in the extent of the lesion (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F8A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f8b.jpeg" height="1280" width="1214" aria-labelledby="F8B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8b.</b>  Atypical neurobehcet lesion in a 30-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> T1-weighted MR image (500/10) shows a large area of low signal intensity (arrow) in the left parietotemporal lobe. <b>(b)</b> Gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (500/10) shows strong enhancement of the masslike lesion, mimicking an abscess. <b>(c)</b> Follow-up MR image obtained after steroid treatment shows a marked decrease in the extent of the lesion (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F8B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f8c.jpeg" height="1280" width="1154" aria-labelledby="F8C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8c.</b>  Atypical neurobehcet lesion in a 30-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> T1-weighted MR image (500/10) shows a large area of low signal intensity (arrow) in the left parietotemporal lobe. <b>(b)</b> Gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (500/10) shows strong enhancement of the masslike lesion, mimicking an abscess. <b>(c)</b> Follow-up MR image obtained after steroid treatment shows a marked decrease in the extent of the lesion (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F8C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f9a.jpeg" height="912" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F9A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9a.</b>  Dural sinus thrombosis in a 43-year-old man. <b>(a, b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT images show an abnormal unenhanced area in both the right sigmoid sinus (arrow in <b>a</b>) and internal jugular vein (circle in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> T2-weighted axial MR image (4000/99) shows the abnormal lack of a signal void (white arrow) in the right sigmoid sinus. A normal signal void (black arrow) is noted in the left sigmoid sinus. <b>(d)</b> Coronal MR image (735/14) obtained after gadolinium administration shows a filling defect (arrowhead), suggesting thrombus in the right sigmoid sinus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F9A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f9b.jpeg" height="962" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F9B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9b.</b>  Dural sinus thrombosis in a 43-year-old man. <b>(a, b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT images show an abnormal unenhanced area in both the right sigmoid sinus (arrow in <b>a</b>) and internal jugular vein (circle in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> T2-weighted axial MR image (4000/99) shows the abnormal lack of a signal void (white arrow) in the right sigmoid sinus. A normal signal void (black arrow) is noted in the left sigmoid sinus. <b>(d)</b> Coronal MR image (735/14) obtained after gadolinium administration shows a filling defect (arrowhead), suggesting thrombus in the right sigmoid sinus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F9B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li><