eads) is noted. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows obliteration of the portal vein and cavernous transformation (arrows). The patient showed no evidence of liver disease on the serologic test or in the pathologic specimen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F13A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f13b.jpeg" height="1099" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F13B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13b.</b>  Occlusion of the portal vein in a 51-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> At ultrasonography, the intrahepatic portal vein is not visualized but a tortuous collateral vein (arrowheads) is noted. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows obliteration of the portal vein and cavernous transformation (arrows). The patient showed no evidence of liver disease on the serologic test or in the pathologic specimen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F13B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f14a.jpeg" height="977" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F14A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 14a.</b>  Peripheral artery aneurysm in a 51-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows a large contrast medium–filled structure (*) with peripheral low attenuation in the left axillary area. These findings suggest an aneurysm. <b>(b)</b> MIP image demonstrates a large saccular aneurysm at the left axillary area.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F14A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f14b.jpeg" height="1280" width="1162" aria-labelledby="F14B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 14b.</b>  Peripheral artery aneurysm in a 51-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows a large contrast medium–filled structure (*) with peripheral low attenuation in the left axillary area. These findings suggest an aneurysm. <b>(b)</b> MIP image demonstrates a large saccular aneurysm at the left axillary area.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F14B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F15A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f15a.jpeg" height="848" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F15A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 15a.</b>  Postoperative pseudoaneurysm recurrence in a 36-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image obtained 6 months after surgery shows the recurrent pseudoaneurysm (*). <b>(b)</b> A sagittally reformatted image shows the saccular shape of the pseudoaneurysm. <b>(c)</b> On an axial CT image, a lobulating soft-tissue lesion (arrowheads) around the pseudoaneurysm suggests perianeurysmal inflammation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F15A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F15B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f15b.gif" height="325" width="440" aria-labelledby="F15B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 15b.</b>  Postoperative pseudoaneurysm recurrence in a 36-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image obtained 6 months after surgery shows the recurrent pseudoaneurysm (*). <b>(b)</b> A sagittally reformatted image shows the saccular shape of the pseudoaneurysm. <b>(c)</b> On an axial CT image, a lobulating soft-tissue lesion (arrowheads) around the pseudoaneurysm suggests perianeurysmal inflammation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F15B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F15C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f15c.jpeg" height="880" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F15C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 15c.</b>  Postoperative pseudoaneurysm recurrence in a 36-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image obtained 6 months after surgery shows the recurrent pseudoaneurysm (*). <b>(b)</b> A sagittally reformatted image shows the saccular shape of the pseudoaneurysm. <b>(c)</b> On an axial CT image, a lobulating soft-tissue lesion (arrowheads) around the pseudoaneurysm suggests perianeurysmal inflammation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F15C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F16" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f16.jpeg" height="1277" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 16.</b>  Renovascular hypertension in a 25-year-old woman. Aortogram shows focal stenosis (arrowhead) in the left renal artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F17" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f17.jpeg" height="1280" width="836" aria-labelledby="F17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 17.</b>  Diffuse arterial occlusion in the lower extremities in a 31-year-old man. At CT angiography, a coronal MIP image shows faint visualization of both superficial femoral arteries (arrowheads). Distal runoff vessels are supplied by collateral vessels (arrow) from the deep femoral arteries.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F18A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f18a.jpeg" height="1179" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F18A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 18a.</b>  Endomyocardial fibrosis in a 43-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows diffuse low attenuation along the endomyocardium of both ventricles (arrows). <b>(b)</b> T2-weighted MR image (4.7/1.3) shows low signal intensity (arrows) along the endomyocardium, indicating endomyocardial fibrosis. <b>(c)</b> Ultrasonogram shows regurgitant flow to the hepatic vein (*), reflecting the right-side heart failure. Endomyocardial fibrosis was confirmed at surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F18A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F18B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f18b.gif" height="382" width="440" aria-labelledby="F18B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 18b.</b>  Endomyocardial fibrosis in a 43-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows diffuse low attenuation along the endomyocardium of both ventricles (arrows). <b>(b)</b> T2-weighted MR image (4.7/1.3) shows low signal intensity (arrows) along the endomyocardium, indicating endomyocardial fibrosis. <b>(c)</b> Ultrasonogram shows regurgitant flow to the hepatic vein (*), reflecting the right-side heart failure. Endomyocardial fibrosis was confirmed at surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F18B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F18C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f18c.jpeg" height="1280" width="1235" aria-labelledby="F18C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 18c.</b>  Endomyocardial fibrosis in a 43-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows diffuse low attenuation along the endomyocardium of both ventricles (arrows). <b>(b)</b> T2-weighted MR image (4.7/1.3) shows low signal intensity (arrows) along the endomyocardium, indicating endomyocardial fibrosis. <b>(c)</b> Ultrasonogram shows regurgitant flow to the hepatic vein (*), reflecting the right-side heart failure. Endomyocardial fibrosis was confirmed at surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F18C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F19A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f19a.jpeg" height="1116" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F19A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 19a.</b>  Endomyocardial fibrosis mimicking Ebstein anomaly in a 39-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT image shows an enlarged right atrium. Obliteration of the SVC and bilateral brachiocephalic veins with internal thrombus (arrow) are also noted. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows the downward displacement of the tricuspid leaflets (arrows), mimicking Ebstein anomaly, which was the preoperative diagnosis. Areas of thick fibrotic tissue lining the entire endomycardium of the right atrium and right ventricle were noted during surgery. <b>(c)</b> On another CT image, a focal aneurysm (*) near the outflow track of the right ventricle is noted adjacent to the fibrotic tissue of the endomyocardium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F19A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F19B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f19b.jpeg" height="1160" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F19B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 19b.</b>  Endomyocardial fibrosis mimicking Ebstein anomaly in a 39-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT image shows an enlarged right atrium. Obliteration of the SVC and bilateral brachiocephalic veins with internal thrombus (arrow) are also noted. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows the downward displacement of the tricuspid leaflets (arrows), mimicking Ebstein anomaly, which was the preoperative diagnosis. Areas of thick fibrotic tissue lining the entire endomycardium of the right atrium and right ventricle were noted during surgery. <b>(c)</b> On another CT image, a focal aneurysm (*) near the outflow track of the right ventricle is noted adjacent to the fibrotic tissue of the endomyocardium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F19B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F19C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f19c.jpeg" height="1280" width="1143" aria-labelledby="F19C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 19c.</b>  Endomyocardial fibrosis mimicking Ebstein anomaly in a 39-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT image shows an enlarged right atrium. Obliteration of the SVC and bilateral brachiocephalic veins with internal thrombus (arrow) are also noted. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows the downward displacement of the tricuspid leaflets (arrows), mimicking Ebstein anomaly, which was the preoperative diagnosis. Areas of thick fibrotic tissue lining the entire endomycardium of the right atrium and right ventricle were noted during surgery. <b>(c)</b> On another CT image, a focal aneurysm (*) near the outflow track of the right ventricle is noted adjacent to the fibrotic tissue of the endomyocardium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F19C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F20" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f20.jpeg" height="1200" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F20" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 20.</b>  Intracardiac thrombus in a 25-year-old man. Axial CT image shows multiple filling defects, suggesting thrombus (arrows) in the right ventricle and in the pulmonary arteries in both lower lobes.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F20">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F21A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f21a.jpeg" height="1093" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F21A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 21a.</b>  Periaortic pseudoaneurysm in a 72-year-old man. (a) Axial CT image shows an abnormal vascular structure (arrow) at the aortic root. <b>(b, c)</b> On reformatted CT images obtained to evaluate the aortic valve, a large vegetation (white arrows) along the right and left coronary cusps and a periaortic pseudoaneurysm (black arrows) between both cusps are seen. These findings mimic infective endocarditis of the aortic valve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F21A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F21B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f21b.jpeg" height="1085" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F21B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 21b.</b>  Periaortic pseudoaneurysm in a 72-year-old man. (a) Axial CT image shows an abnormal vascular structure (arrow) at the aortic root. <b>(b, c)</b> On reformatted CT images obtained to evaluate the aortic valve, a large vegetation (white arrows) along the right and left coronary cusps and a periaortic pseudoaneurysm (black arrows) between both cusps are seen. These findings mimic infective endocarditis of the aortic valve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F21B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F21C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f21c.gif" height="350" width="440" aria-labelledby="F21C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 21c.</b>  Periaortic pseudoaneurysm in a 72-year-old man. (a) Axial CT image shows an abnormal vascular structure (arrow) at the aortic root. <b>(b, c)</b> On reformatted CT images obtained to evaluate the aortic valve, a large vegetation (white arrows) along the right and left coronary cusps and a periaortic pseudoaneurysm (black arrows) between both cusps are seen. These findings mimic infective endocarditis of the aortic valve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F21C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F22A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f22a.jpeg" height="1280" width="1273" aria-labelledby="F22A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 22a.</b>  Postoperative paravalvular leakage in a 44-year-old woman. This patient had undergone removal of a periaortic abscess and patch closure of the left ventricular outflow track. Her preoperative diagnosis was infective endocarditis. <b>(a)</b> Postoperative CT image shows a new, contrast medium–filled structure (arrows) with a 5-cm largest diameter in the posterior paravalvular area. <b>(b)</b> Sagittally reformatted CT image also shows the abnormal vascular structure (*), representing paravalvular leakage and indicating recurrent aortitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F22A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F22B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f22b.jpeg" height="1280" width="873" aria-labelledby="F22B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 22b.</b>  Postoperative paravalvular leakage in a 44-year-old woman. This patient had undergone removal of a periaortic abscess and patch closure of the left ventricular outflow track. Her preoperative diagnosis was infective endocarditis. <b>(a)</b> Postoperative CT image shows a new, contrast medium–filled structure (arrows) with a 5-cm largest diameter in the posterior paravalvular area. <b>(b)</b> Sagittally reformatted CT image also shows the abnormal vascular structure (*), representing paravalvular leakage and indicating recurrent aortitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F22B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F23A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f23a.jpeg" height="1162" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F23A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 23a.</b>  Rupture of the sinus of Valsalva in a 23-year-old man with orthopnea. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows a large bizarre-shaped pseudoaneurym (black arrows) with partial thrombi (white arrows) on the right side of the aortic root. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image shows a lobulating, contoured, low-attenuation lesion suggesting confined thrombus (arrows) along the right side of the aortic root. Rupture of the sinus of Valsalva was confirmed at surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F23A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F23B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f23b.jpeg" height="1280" width="1179" aria-labelledby="F23B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 23b.</b>  Rupture of the sinus of Valsalva in a 23-year-old man with orthopnea. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows a large bizarre-shaped pseudoaneurym (black arrows) with partial thrombi (white arrows) on the right side of the aortic root. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image shows a lobulating, contoured, low-attenuation lesion suggesting confined thrombus (arrows) along the right side of the aortic root. Rupture of the sinus of Valsalva was confirmed at surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F23B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F24A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f24a.jpeg" height="1280" width="763" aria-labelledby="F24A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 24a.</b>  Ascending aortic aneurysm in a 34-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows the mildly bulging contour (arrow) of the ascending thoracic aorta. <b>(b)</b> Coronally reformatted CT image shows a fusiform aneurysm involving the ascending aorta, aortic arch, and the proximal descending aorta. <b>(c)</b> CT image reformatted to evaluate the aortic valve shows a coaptation defect (arrow) in the aortic valve during the diastolic phase.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F24A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F24B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f24b.jpeg" height="1280" width="779" aria-labelledby="F24B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 24b.</b>  Ascending aortic aneurysm in a 34-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows the mildly bulging contour (arrow) of the ascending thoracic aorta. <b>(b)</b> Coronally reformatted CT image shows a fusiform aneurysm involving the ascending aorta, aortic arch, and the proximal descending aorta. <b>(c)</b> CT image reformatted to evaluate the aortic valve shows a coaptation defect (arrow) in the aortic valve during the diastolic phase.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F24B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F24C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f24c.gif" height="440" width="431" aria-labelledby="F24C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 24c.</b>  Ascending aortic aneurysm in a 34-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows the mildly bulging contour (arrow) of the ascending thoracic aorta. <b>(b)</b> Coronally reformatted CT image shows a fusiform aneurysm involving the ascending aorta, aortic arch, and the proximal descending aorta. <b>(c)</b> CT image reformatted to evaluate the aortic valve shows a coaptation defect (arrow) in the aortic valve during the diastolic phase.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F24C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F25A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f25a.jpeg" height="1103" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F25A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 25a.</b>  Pulmonary artery aneurysm in a 36-year-old man complaining of hemoptysis. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows a masslike area of increased opacity in the right infrahilar region. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows that the pulmonary arteries in both lower lobes are dilated (arrows). A filling defect (arrowhead) with low attenuation is seen in the right ventricle. <b>(c)</b> At bronchoscopy, the anterior basal segmental bronchus is indented (arrows) owing to extrinsic compression by the pulmonary artery aneurysm. <b>(d)</b> Follow-up chest radiograph and <b>(e)</b> CT image obtained 4 years later show a marked decrease in the size of the aneurysm (arrows in <b>e</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F25A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F25B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f25b.jpeg" height="907" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F25B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 25b.</b>  Pulmonary artery aneurysm in a 36-year-old man complaining of hemoptysis. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows a masslike area of increased opacity in the right infrahilar region. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows that the pulmonary arteries in both lower lobes are dilated (arrows). A filling defect (arrowhead) with low attenuation is seen in the right ventricle. <b>(c)</b> At bronchoscopy, the anterior basal segmental bronchus is indented (arrows) owing to extrinsic compression by the pulmonary artery aneurysm. <b>(d)</b> Follow-up chest radiograph and <b>(e)</b> CT image obtained 4 years later show a marked decrease in the size of the aneurysm (arrows in <b>e</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li>