ysm. <b>(d)</b> Follow-up chest radiograph and <b>(e)</b> CT image obtained 4 years later show a marked decrease in the size of the aneurysm (arrows in <b>e</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F25D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F25E" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f25e.jpeg" height="917" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F25E" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 25e.</b>  Pulmonary artery aneurysm in a 36-year-old man complaining of hemoptysis. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows a masslike area of increased opacity in the right infrahilar region. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows that the pulmonary arteries in both lower lobes are dilated (arrows). A filling defect (arrowhead) with low attenuation is seen in the right ventricle. <b>(c)</b> At bronchoscopy, the anterior basal segmental bronchus is indented (arrows) owing to extrinsic compression by the pulmonary artery aneurysm. <b>(d)</b> Follow-up chest radiograph and <b>(e)</b> CT image obtained 4 years later show a marked decrease in the size of the aneurysm (arrows in <b>e</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F25E">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F26A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f26a.jpeg" height="882" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F26A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 26a.</b>  Chronic pulmonary artery thromboembolism in a 56-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows dilatation of the main pulmonary trunk (*), suggesting pulmonary artery hypertension. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image also shows a weblike structure (arrowhead) in the pulmonary artery. <b>(c)</b> On a coronally reformatted CT image and <b>(d)</b> on a pulmonary angiogram, sparse pulmonary vascularity in the right lung (dotted circles) and clubbing of the truncus anterior (arrow in <b>c</b>) are noted. <b>(e)</b> Lung window setting CT image shows a mosaic attenuation of lung parenchyma. <b>(f)</b> Radionuclide scintigraphy shows multiple perfusion defects in both lungs.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F26A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F26B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f26b.jpeg" height="803" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F26B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 26b.</b>  Chronic pulmonary artery thromboembolism in a 56-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows dilatation of the main pulmonary trunk (*), suggesting pulmonary artery hypertension. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image also shows a weblike structure (arrowhead) in the pulmonary artery. <b>(c)</b> On a coronally reformatted CT image and <b>(d)</b> on a pulmonary angiogram, sparse pulmonary vascularity in the right lung (dotted circles) and clubbing of the truncus anterior (arrow in <b>c</b>) are noted. <b>(e)</b> Lung window setting CT image shows a mosaic attenuation of lung parenchyma. <b>(f)</b> Radionuclide scintigraphy shows multiple perfusion defects in both lungs.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F26B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F26C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f26c.jpeg" height="1210" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F26C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 26c.</b>  Chronic pulmonary artery thromboembolism in a 56-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows dilatation of the main pulmonary trunk (*), suggesting pulmonary artery hypertension. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image also shows a weblike structure (arrowhead) in the pulmonary artery. <b>(c)</b> On a coronally reformatted CT image and <b>(d)</b> on a pulmonary angiogram, sparse pulmonary vascularity in the right lung (dotted circles) and clubbing of the truncus anterior (arrow in <b>c</b>) are noted. <b>(e)</b> Lung window setting CT image shows a mosaic attenuation of lung parenchyma. <b>(f)</b> Radionuclide scintigraphy shows multiple perfusion defects in both lungs.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F26C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F26D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f26d.jpeg" height="1280" width="1164" aria-labelledby="F26D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 26d.</b>  Chronic pulmonary artery thromboembolism in a 56-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows dilatation of the main pulmonary trunk (*), suggesting pulmonary artery hypertension. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image also shows a weblike structure (arrowhead) in the pulmonary artery. <b>(c)</b> On a coronally reformatted CT image and <b>(d)</b> on a pulmonary angiogram, sparse pulmonary vascularity in the right lung (dotted circles) and clubbing of the truncus anterior (arrow in <b>c</b>) are noted. <b>(e)</b> Lung window setting CT image shows a mosaic attenuation of lung parenchyma. <b>(f)</b> Radionuclide scintigraphy shows multiple perfusion defects in both lungs.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F26D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F26E" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f26e.jpeg" height="891" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F26E" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 26e.</b>  Chronic pulmonary artery thromboembolism in a 56-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows dilatation of the main pulmonary trunk (*), suggesting pulmonary artery hypertension. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image also shows a weblike structure (arrowhead) in the pulmonary artery. <b>(c)</b> On a coronally reformatted CT image and <b>(d)</b> on a pulmonary angiogram, sparse pulmonary vascularity in the right lung (dotted circles) and clubbing of the truncus anterior (arrow in <b>c</b>) are noted. <b>(e)</b> Lung window setting CT image shows a mosaic attenuation of lung parenchyma. <b>(f)</b> Radionuclide scintigraphy shows multiple perfusion defects in both lungs.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F26E">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F26F" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f26f.jpeg" height="1280" width="1122" aria-labelledby="F26F" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 26f.</b>  Chronic pulmonary artery thromboembolism in a 56-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows dilatation of the main pulmonary trunk (*), suggesting pulmonary artery hypertension. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image also shows a weblike structure (arrowhead) in the pulmonary artery. <b>(c)</b> On a coronally reformatted CT image and <b>(d)</b> on a pulmonary angiogram, sparse pulmonary vascularity in the right lung (dotted circles) and clubbing of the truncus anterior (arrow in <b>c</b>) are noted. <b>(e)</b> Lung window setting CT image shows a mosaic attenuation of lung parenchyma. <b>(f)</b> Radionuclide scintigraphy shows multiple perfusion defects in both lungs.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F26F">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F27A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f27a.jpeg" height="1280" width="814" aria-labelledby="F27A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 27a.</b>  SVC syndrome in a 27-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows widening of the upper mediastinum. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows a filling defect (arrow) in the right brachiocephalic vein. <b>(c)</b> Coronal CT image shows that the thrombus (arrowhead) also involves the left brachiocephalic vein. Mediastinal edema and collateral vessels are noted in both the lower neck and mediastinum. <b>(d)</b> Follow-up CT image obtained 1 year later shows obliteration of the SVC (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F27A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F27B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f27b.jpeg" height="559" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F27B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 27b.</b>  SVC syndrome in a 27-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows widening of the upper mediastinum. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows a filling defect (arrow) in the right brachiocephalic vein. <b>(c)</b> Coronal CT image shows that the thrombus (arrowhead) also involves the left brachiocephalic vein. Mediastinal edema and collateral vessels are noted in both the lower neck and mediastinum. <b>(d)</b> Follow-up CT image obtained 1 year later shows obliteration of the SVC (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F27B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F27C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f27c.jpeg" height="1265" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F27C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 27c.</b>  SVC syndrome in a 27-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows widening of the upper mediastinum. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows a filling defect (arrow) in the right brachiocephalic vein. <b>(c)</b> Coronal CT image shows that the thrombus (arrowhead) also involves the left brachiocephalic vein. Mediastinal edema and collateral vessels are noted in both the lower neck and mediastinum. <b>(d)</b> Follow-up CT image obtained 1 year later shows obliteration of the SVC (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F27C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F27D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e31/asset/images/e31f27d.jpeg" height="1280" width="1065" aria-labelledby="F27D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 27d.</b>  SVC syndrome in a 27-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows widening of the upper mediastinum. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows a filling defect (arrow) in the right brachiocephalic vein. <b>(c)</b> Coronal CT image shows that the thrombus (arrowhead) also involves the left brachiocephalic vein. Mediastinal edema and collateral vessels are noted in both the lower neck and mediastinum. <b>(d)</b> Follow-up CT image obtained 1 year later shows obliteration of the SVC (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e31&amp;id=F27D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="T1" class="table"><figcaption><span class="heading">Table 1</span>. <b>Frequency of Occurrence of Various Lesions in Behçet Disease in Previous Literature Reports</b></figcaption><img src="/cms/10.1148